          "id": 1,
          "question": "<p><a name=\"61088\"></a><div itemprop=\"text\"><p>In the case of parallelization, Amdahl's law states that if \\( P \\) is the proportion of a program that can be made parallel and \\( (1-P) \\) is the proportion that cannot be parallelized, then the maximum speed-up that can be achieved by using \\( N \\) processors is:</p>\n\n</div><br><br><b>CO & Architecture: UGC NET CSE | Junet 2015 | Part 2 | Question: 46</b></p>",
          "type": "single",
          "options": [
            "<p>\\( \\dfrac{1}{(1-P)+N.P} \\\\ \\)</p>",
            "<p>\\( \\dfrac{1}{(N-1)P+P} \\\\ \\)</p>",
            "<p>\\( \\dfrac{1}{(1-P)+\\frac{P}{N}} \\\\ \\)</p>",
            "<p>\\( \\dfrac{1}{P+\\frac{(1-P)}{N}} \\)</p>"
          ],
          "correct_answer": "<p>\\( \\dfrac{1}{(1-P)+\\frac{P}{N}} \\\\ \\)</p>",
